Abdominal terga 3­5 with moderate transverse basal impressions. Tergum 7 1.2­1.3 times as long as tergum 6 . Puncturation on terga 6­7 sparser than on terga 3­5 . Female sternum 8 (
Figs. 32­33
) with row of apical microsetae (as in other Athetini ).

Some characters previously used in keys to distinguish species of
Geostiba
(
Lohse & Smetana 1988
;
Pace 1997
) are found to be of limited utility. For example, the microsculpture of the abdominal tergum 7 is similar in all native Nearctic species. In the basal portion of the tergum the microsculpture consists of transverse meshes, while in the apical portion it consists of isodiametric or even elongate meshes ( Figs. 56 ,
99 , 125 , 151 , 192 , 218
). I did not count the number of ommatidia in the eyes but instead compared eye length to temple length.
